

Basic scripting

The script language compiles plain ASCII text files: document formats from
word processors cannot be used. A text editor is recommended for creating
script files. The blocks of text are read into the compiler, ignoring
leading tabs and spaces,  and interpreted into a machine format that
Legends of Future Past interprets as players interact with the game. Lines
of text in the script file that begin with a semicolon are ignored as
"comment lines." It is not case-sensitive.

Nouns

The most simple element of the script language is the ability to define
all the nouns and adjectives that Legends will recognize. This is done
with the NOUNDEF and ADJDEF commands, which take the format NOUNDEF [noun
#] [noun name].

        Examples:
                        NOUNDEF 0 agate
                        NOUNDEF 1 alexandrite
                        NOUNDEF 2 amethyst
                        NOUNDEF 3 altar
                        NOUNDEF 4 amulet
                        NOUNDEF 5 anklet
                        NOUNDEF 6 aquamarine
                        NOUNDEF 7 arch

                        ADJDEF 0 acid
                        ADJDEF 1aelfen
                        ADJDEF 2 alexandrite
                        ADJDEF 3 alkyline
                        ADJDEF 4 amazing
                        ADJDEF 5 alzyron
                        ADJDEF 6 amethyst
                        ADJDEF 7 ancient


FORAGEDEF <terrain> <item#> <adjective#> <ratio> <val2> <val5>

This is a definition that states that item# can be found in a room of type
<terrain>. The "ratio" variable determines the likelihood of finding this
particular item relative to anything else in the area (for example, if one
item has a ratio of 10 and another has a ratio of 20, then the second item
will be found twice as often as the first). The room terrain for <terrain>
is limited to FOREST, MOUNTAIN, PLAIN, SWAMP and JUNGLE. Items should only
be
forageable if they are prevalent throughout a particular terrain type and
if they are generally available throughout all seasons.

MINDEF <item#> <adjective#> <grade> <copper value> <val2>

This is a definition that states that item# with adjective# is a mineable
item of "grade" (the latter of which may be 'A', 'B', or 'C', in
descending value).

Defining items

Before an item can be placed in your room description they must be
defined. By capturing a @list of items or @scanning for a particular item
name you can determine if what you want is already in the system. Even
with the large amount of items already available you will find it
necessary, at some time, to script a new item.

You will begin all item definitions with the INUMBER command, which takes
the format INUMBER #. Before you assign the item you are making a number
you must be assigned a block of blank item numbers with which to work.
Always use the lowest item number you
are assigned and work upwards.

The first thing that every item needs is a name. To give the item a name,
use the NAME command which takes the format NAME [noun #]. Now that you
have defined the INUMBER and the NAME of the tiem there are a variety of
other things that must now be defined as well.

Item type: On a line by itself choose one of the following that best
describes your item. If left undefined, the script assumes it to be MISC
(miscellaneous).

        AMMO             | Ammunition (arrows, bolts, bullets)
        ARMOR            | Anything worn for protection
        BITE_WEAPON      | Teeth, jaws, etc. used by monsters
        BOW_WEAPON       | Any archaic missle weapon(bows, handguns)
        CLAW_WEAPON      | Claws, etc. that belongs to monsters
        CRUSH_WEAPON     | Crushing weapons
        DRAKIN_CRUSH     | Drakin (oriental) crushing weapons
        DRAKIN_POLE      | Drakin polearms
        DRAKIN_SLASH     | Drakin slashing weapons
        DRAKIN_THROWN    | Drakin thrown weapons
        FOOD             | Any item that is edible
        HANDGUN          | Technological one hand missle  weapons
        KEY              | Anything that can be used to unlock items
        LIQCONTAINER     | A liquid container (flasks, jugs)
        LIQUID           | Any item that is drinkable
        LOCKPICK         | Any item used for springing locks
        MINETOOL         | Mining implements (Pickaxe, shovel)
        MISC             | Anything that won't fit in elsewhere
        MONEY            | Coins
        POLE_WEAPON      | Polearms (halberds, glaives, lances)
        POLETHROWN       | Polearms that can be thrown (spears..)
        PORTAL_THROUGH   | Doors, archways, etc.
        PORTAL_CLIMB     | Ropes, ladders, etc.
        PORTAL_UP        | Ramps, trails, paths, etc.
        PORTAL_DOWN      | Ramps, trails, paths
        PUNCTURE_WEAPON  | Puncturing weapons (rapiers, stillettos)
        RIFLE            | Large technological missle weapons
        SCROLL           | Magical scrolls
        SHIELD           | Shields
        SLASH_WEAPON     | Slashing weapons (swords, axes)
        STABTHROWN       | Weapons that can stab or be thrown (dagger)
        THROWN_WEAPON    | darts, rocks
        TRAP             | Traps
        TWOHAND_WEAPON   | Two handed edged weapons
(greatswords,                                battleaxes)

ORE
Ore can be sold or it can be smelted by a character with weaponsmithing
skill and then worked into the form of a weapon. PARAMETER2 defines the
new item archetype created when the ore is refined. The VAL2 field of an
ORE item is transferred to any new item it is worked into. The VAL3 field
of an ORE item is its purity, i.e., how much useful metal is contained in
the amount of rock. This represents a percentage chance that a smith has
of refining any useful metal from the ore. The PARAMETER1 field has
multiple
meanings. If it equals -1, then no adjective is placed on a new item
constructed from the material. If it is zero, then the old adjectives of
the material are transferred to the adjective to place on a new item
created from the material. The PARAMETER3 field specifies the grade of the
ore.

WEIGHT [pounds]

This is simply the weight of the item in pounds.  Any object with a weight
of 1000 or more is not moveable by the players (they can't pick it up and
take it with them, etc.). Doors, trails, and other such permanent items
should be defined as having a weight of 1000.

VOLUME [amount]

This is an abstract value representing the amount of space that item will
take up. It is not based upon any type of "real" volume.  This value
limits what can be put in what containers, e.g. a great sword can not fit
in a lock box.  The rough valumne equivalent are as follows:

1-Keys, arrows, daggers, gems or smaller
2-Hand axe
3-Light crossbow
4-Club
5-Short sword, light armor
6-Short bow, scimitar, long sword
7-Greatsword
8-Long bow, polearm, full armor
9+- Very large objects, probably to big to carry

SUBSTANCE [substance type]

This describes the type of material the object is made of. If the exact
substance is unavailable, then choose the thing that is closest in
hardness and durability. If an object is made of more than one material
(e.g., a hand axe is made of a metal head and a wooden shaft) chose a
substance type which is an average of the two types. If left undefined,
the substances is assumed to be INDESTRUCTRABLE.  The substance types are:

INSUBSTANTIAL
Gas and liquids

PAPER
Scrolls, letters

CLOTH
Clothing, ropes

BRITTLE
Glass bottles, gems

WOOD
Anything made of wood

STONE
Primitive stone tools, harder gems, etc.

SOFTMETAL
Softer metals (silver, gold, tin, brass)

HARDMETAL
Harder metals (iron, steel, titanium)

INDESTRUCTABLE
Anything extremely hard (Alzyron or magical metals) or otherwise
indestructable for reasons of game integrity (Doors, trails, etc.)

ARTICLE [A|AN|THE|SOME]

If left undefined "ARTICLE A" is assumed. This defines how the game refers
to the object, i.e., is it "a sunsword," "some sunsword" or "the sunsword."

CONTAINER [type]

Defines the object as a type of container, i.e., any object that can have
something put on, in, under or behind it. No object may contain items in
two different ways (e.g., a bed could have things able to be put on it or
under it, but not both).

INTERIOR [amount]

This value is only necessary for items that will act as containers of some
sort. It defines how much the container can hold, it may contain uup to
[amount] in total volume of items, as defined by the VOLUMNE definitions
of the contained items. Note howeve,r that the container's VOLUME value
itself also comes into play when the game is determining whether or not an
object can fit in the container: if the item to be contained is equal to
or greater than the container's VOLUME, it won't fit.

PARAMETER1 [value]

Defines a value for special parameter 31. It is unnecessary for most
items.  Fo liquids, it is the amount of drinks that can be taken from it
before it runs out (and if over 100, it is treated as unlimited). For
weapons, it defines the maximum damage the weapon will do and for armor it
defines the percentage of damage that the armor absorbs. Keep in mind the
values given for other such items when deciding on what this value should
be. The usefulness of this parameter may be expanded in the future.

PARAMETER2 [value]

Defines a value for special parameter2. It is unnecessary for most items.
For missile weapons, it defines the item number to be used as its
ammunition type. For ammunition, it defines the number of individual units
of ammunition are included in a bundle.
The usefulness of this parameter may be expanded in the future.

PARAMETER3 [value]

This is similar to PARAMETER1 and PARAMETER2 on items. It will be used for
more complex item archetypes in the future.

Additional parameters: Any of the following may appear on a line by
themselves to define special information about an object. You could use
one of them, none of them or any combination of them.

CRAFTABLE
When placed on an item, it makes that item available for crafting by a
player craftsman. Be carefull with this. Players are limited as to what
craftable items they can actually make as follows: if an item is a weapon,
then the player's smithing skill must
>= the weapons parameter1 field. If it is a piece of armor, it is limited
by one-third the armors weight. If it is a piece of clothing or jewelry it
is limited by whatever parameter2 happens to be. NOTE: No more than one
item should be craftable per noun.


DYEABLE
This is an item modifier that states that the given item archetype can be
died, assuming it has no adjectives in slots #1 or #2.

ENCRUSTABLE
This makes it possible to use the INSET, INLAY, ENCRUST and similar verbs
on an item.

DYE
This is an item modifier that can be used with other item definitions.
When defined, it allows anyone with Dyer/weaver skill to extract the
pigment from the object and use it to color a cloth item. On DYE items,
PARAMETER1 defines the #1 adjective and PARAMETER3 defines the #2
adjective to place on an item it is dyed with. A different archetype needs
to be made for every item that can dye a different color.

FLIPABLE
Items may be flipped (as in a switch)

HIDDEN
Item is hidden from being listed with other objects in the room.

LATCHABLE
Item can latch shut. Items that are latched can't be opened.

LIGHTABLE
Item will shed light.

LOCKABLE
Item can be locked.

REAGENT
If it is set then the val5 field of this item will determine what type of
reagent it is.

Reagent type
------------

1=Power 1
2=Power 2
3=Power 3
4=Health
5=Harm
6=Body
7=Resist
8=Enhancement
9=Miscellaneous, common
10=Miscellaneuos, uncommon
11=Miscellaneous, rare
12=Mind
13=Protect

SKIN
Allows you to make an item available for skinning from a monster.

TURNABLE
Item can be turned.

WORN_AROUND
Item may be worn around the body (belts, girdles, etc.)

WORN_BACK
Capes, backpacks, etc.

WORN_BODY
Robes, Trenchcoats, etc.

WORN_DON
This is reserved for accesory items like medals, badges, sunglasses, etc.

WORN_EAR
Earrings, earcuffs, etc.

WORN_FEET1
Socks, stockings, etc.

WORN_FEET2
Shoes, boots, etc.

WORN_HAIR
Hairpins, barrettes, etc.

WORN_HANDS
Gloves, gauntlets, etc.

WORN_HEAD
Hats, helmets, etc.

WORN_NECK
Torcs, amulets, etc.

WORN_RING
Anything worn around the finger.

WORN_TORSO1
Bras, undershirts, etc.

WORN_TORSO2
Shirts, blouses, etc.

WORN_TORSO3
Jackets, vests, etc.

WORN_TRUNK1
Panties, boxers, etc.

WORN_TRUNK2
Breeches, skirts, etc.

WORN_WRIST
Bracers, bracelets, etc.

CONTAINER IN

CONTAINER UNDER

CONTAINER ON

CONTAINER BEHIND


Example of items:
-----------------

Example 1: Sword (long based)
           INUMBER 46
           NAME 201
           WEAIGHT 4
           VOLUME 6
           PARAMETER1 8
           SLASH_WEAPON
           SUBSTANCE HARDMETAL

Example 2:  Mail (double chain based)
            INUMBER 53
            NAME 130
            WEIGHT 40
            VOLUME 5
            PARAMETER1 35
            WORN_ARMOR
            ARMOR
            ARTICLE SOME
            SUBSTANCE HARDMETAL

Example 3:  Arch
            INUMBER 60
            NAME 7
            PORTAL
            WEIGHT 1000
            VOLUME 28
            HIDDEN

Example 4:  Chest (small based)
            INUMBER 87
            NAME 49
            WEIGHT 10
            VOLUME 6
            INTERIOR 10
            CONTAINER IN
            MISC
            LOCKABLE
            OPENABLE
            SUBSTANCE SOFTMETAL

Example 5: The following is a complex example of item scripting. It
           contains a number of  advanced principles that will be
           explained later in  this document.

INUMBER 1617
NAME 32
WEIGHT 4
VOLUME 4
BOW_WEAPON
PARAMETER1 15
PARAMETER2 0
WORN_DON
SUBSTANCE INDESTRUCTABLE
VARIABLE SHOOTER
IFSEEK 180
IFVERB CONCENTRATE -1
IFVAR ITEMVAL5 ! TIM
ADD SHOOTER 1
IFVAR SHOOTER < 20
ECHO PLAYER May your aim be true.
SPELL 512 30
ECHO Player Let your enemies not harm you.
SPELL 133 50
ENDIF
IFVAR SHOOTER > 20
EQUAL ITEMVAL5 TIM
ENDIF
ENDIF
ENDIF
IFVERB LISTEN -1
ECHO PLAYER For you and only for you I shall reveal the full extent of my
ECHO PLAYER powers. If you have need of protection and steady hands you
have
ECHO player only to concentrate on me. Should you need your health restored
ECHO player polish me to a high luster. If you are bleeding and in need of
ECHO PLAYER staunching the flow of blood then sling me onto your back. If
you
ECHO PLAYER ever need light to see by gain my attention by tapping me.
ENDIF
IFVERB WEAR -1
ECHO PLAYER You sling the bow over your shoulder.
SPELL 342 50
ENDIF
IFPREVERB GIVE -1
ECHO PLAYER I am for you and no other. I shall be touched by no other hand.
ECHO OTHERS %n gets a glazed look for a moment and then nods his head
absently.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB DROP -1
ECHO PLAYER I shall not leave your hand we are as one now.
ECHO OTHERS %n looks like he is about to set the bow down and then changes
his mind.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB PUT -1
ECHO PLAYER No, I will not be seperated from you.
ECHO OTHERS %n grasps the bow tightly.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFITEM -1 WIELDED
IFVERB LOAD -1
ECHO ALL As the bow is loaded the arrow shimmers magically.
ENDIF
IFVERB RUB -1
ECHO PLAYER As you polish the bow lovingly, it glows a soft blue and
speaks to you:
ECHO PLAYER Let my power heal thy wounds.
ECHO OTHERS %n polishes the bow to a high luster, a soft blue glow
surrounds him.
EQUAL ROUNDTIME 20
SPELL 318
ENDIF
IFVERB TAP -1
ECHO OTHERS The bow flares with a brilliant blue light that coalesces into
a floating orb.
SPELL 113 50
ENDIF
ENDIF
ENDIF


Item scripting cont'd.
----------------------
SEALED
This modifier is to be used in an portal that, when closed, may not be
seeped through if a player is in mist form. Use it on portals such as
Gates, Doors, trapdoors, etc.


Defining Rooms
--------------

Every room has to have certain parameters defined for it. This includes
the room number, a name, the terrain, the lighting and a description.
These are the parameters that must be included in the script. Later, we
will discuss additional modifiers and conditional statements that you can
add to 'spice' it up.

Number
The compiler recognizes that you are defining a room when you use the
NUMBER command. It takes the format NUMBER [#] where # is the number of
the room you are defining.


To give your room a name use the NAME command on a line by itself after
defining the number of the room. The format is NAME [text].

Room Descriptions

The description isentered by placing *DESCRIPTION_START on a line by
itself, entering the text for the description on following lines and
ending it with *DESCRIPTION_END on a line by itself. Warning: Remember to
end the description with the proper statement. Also make sure it is
correctly spelled. If you forget or mispell the ending
statement you will have all of the script that follows  included in the
room description until it encounters a *DESCRIPTION_END.

Example:
        *DESCRIPTION_START
        This is a room like many other rooms.
        *DESCRIPTION_END

Terrain

Terrain is defined by entering one of the following that best describe it
on a line by itself after the *DESCRIPTION_END.. The possible terrains are:

INDOOR_FLOOR
Any room, inside a building, with a man made floor.
INDOOR_GROUND
Any room inside a building with a dirt floor.

CAVE
Used for shallow caves and caverns.

DEEPCAVE
Used for caverns so far underground that a large variety of spells will
not function.

FOREST

MOUNTAIN
PLAIN

SWAMP

JUNGLE

WASTE

OUTDOOR_OTHER

OUTDOOR_FLOOR
Used in exposed ruins and such.

AERIAL

ASTRAL

UNDERSEA


Lighting
Lighting is defined as:

FIXED_LIGHT

DARKNESS

PARTIAL_DARKNESS

DAY_LIGHT

OBSCURED_DAY_LIGHT


Room Modifiers

FORGE
Defines a room to have a fully equipped forge for weaponsmiths and
jewelers.

LOOM
Defines a room as having a fully equipped loo for Dyers\weavers where
appropriate substances may be turned into clothing.

MINEA
Defines a room as having minerals of grade A (the best). Grade B and C ore
will also appear in this room.

MINEB
Defines a room as having minerals of grade B (average). Grade C ore will
also appear in this room.

MINEC
Defines a room as having minerals of grade C (the worst).
BUY_ARMOR
States that it is possible to sell armor and weapons to a merchant in this
room.

BUY_SKINS
States that it is possible to sell skins in this room.

BUY_JEWELRY
States that it is possible to sell jewelry, gems and art objects in the
room.

SUBMERGED
Defines a room as being underwater.

MOVEMENT_ASTRAL

Note: All room modifiers are mutually exclusive. If you have two
types of modifiers in one room the system will only acknowledge the last
one listed. The same applies to Terrain types.


Example of a simple room:

NUMBER 165
NAME Matriarch tree, hallway
*DESCRIPTION_START
A long hallway allows you to travers the full width of this huge
tree. Its wooden floors are deeply polished. Delicately papered with
a pink flocking and finished with marble panels, the corridor speaks of a
long forgotten time of opulence.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT O 101
EXIT W 166
INDOOR_FLOOR
DARKNESS

Placing Items in rooms
----------------------

To have items automayically appear inside a room you create, use the ITEM
command inside the block of script that defines the room. The format for
this is ITEM [reference #0-9] [item archetype] [additional parameters].
The reference number is used later in the room scripts for any conditional
statements or descriptions you attach to the item. (conditional statements
will be discussed later in this document.) The ARCHETYPE # is just the
INUMBER of the item that you wish to place in the room. The additional
parameters are as follows.

ADJ1= [ADJECTIVE #]
ADJ2=       "
ADJ3=       "
VAL1=[discussed immediately after]
VAL2=       "
VAL3=       "
VAL4=       "
VAL5=       "

CLOSED
The item is closed.

FLIPPED
The item is flipped.

LATCHED
The item is latched

LIT
Item is lit.

LOCKED
Item is locked

OPEN
Item is open.

UNFLIPPED

UNLATCHED

UNLIT

UNLOCKED

PUT
The put command is similar to the ITEM command. Its format is equivalent,
except in this case, [reference #] indicates that the item will be put on,
in, etc. the object already defined in this room as [reference #]. NOTE:
Items palced with the put command cannot be referenced back to as can
those placed by ITEM.

Example room containing an ITEM (portal)
NUMBER 120
NAME Grymwood, bone yard.
MONSTER_GROUP 9
*DESCRIPTION_START
A rocky clearing opens from a narrow crevice to the south and a
well-marked trail to the west. The ground appears to be covered with a
coarse white gravel. On close inspection, however, you discover that it is
made up of millions of sun bleached bone fragments.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT W 107
EXIT ABOVE 2125
ITEM 0 63 ADJ1=210 VAL2=119
FOREST
DAY_LIGHT

Example of room with many items.

NUMBER 385
NAME Palace, throne room
MONSTER_GROUP 15
INDOOR_FLOOR
FIXED_LIGHT
*DESCRIPTION_START
A red silk rug leads to the Royal Throne at the northern end of this room.
The carpet is arrayed with smooth blue stone pillars at even intervals on
each side. A solid gold throne sits on top og a dais. Soft purple velvet
pillows are spread out at its feet. A stylized shield hangs above the
throne, suspended on two chains with the Royal Creast engraved upon its
face. The dais also accomodates two similar thrones for the Queen and
Prince.
*DESCRIPTION_END
ITEM 0 65 ADJ1=468 VAL2=382
ITEM 1 362 ADJ1=259 ADJ2=291
ITEM 2 542 ADJ1=147
ITEM 3 542 ADJ1= 294
ITEM 4 542 ADJ1=294
ITEM 5 59
EXTEND 5 with the Royal Crest engraved on it
ITEM 6 193 ADJ1=298 ADJ2=248 ADJ3=337

Item Value Fields

The item value fields which are defined with VALx=y in the ITEM, PUT,
NEWPUT and NEWITEM script commands, and editable with the @editem and
@ednumber GM command. The function of the VAL fields may be expanded with
time. The current uses of these fields are as follows:

VAL1
If it is a lockable item , this is the lock modifier. The higher the
number the harder the lock. If it is treasure or an item that may be sold,
this is the copper value of the item. If it is an item type MONEY, it is
the number of coins present.

VAL2
If this item is a portal type, this indicates the destination room of the
portal. If it is a weapon or armor this indicates the magical bonus (or
penalty) of the item. If it is a charged spell casting item, it is the
number of charges. If it is a liquid or food item it indicates the number
of sips or bites, respectively. If it is MONEY it indicates the player
that dropped it or -1 if it is from an unknown source.

VAL3
If it is a lockable item it indicates the item number which will unlock
it. If it is a KEY item it indicates what the item opens. If it is a magic
item it indicates what spell is cast. If it is a missle weapon and is set
to 0 it indicates the missle weapon is unloaded, if it indicates any value
above 0 it indicates the missle  weapon is loaded. If it is a hand to hand
weapon it indicates the special power of the weapon(Flare crits, slaying,
etc.)

VAL4
This defines what type of trap or glyph is on the weapon. The avalailable
traps are:
1-Needle with minor poison
2-Poison gas with minor damage
3-Acid resevoir which causes burn damage and dissolves lockpick
4-Spring loaded blades
5-Needle with moderate poison
7-Needle with major poison
8-Explosive, destroys objects and contents
9-Acid resevoir as #3 but larger damage
12-Nerve gas
13-Needle with lethal posion
1001-Inferno Glyph
3001-Ice Glyph
5001- Thunder Glyph
7001-Imprisonment Rune
9001-Symbol of Death

VAL5
At this time it is only used in certain conditional statements and, if
placed on a weapon with a special power, define how much extra damage is
done.(The special powers of weapons will be discussed later in this
document.)

Example of a room with many items, some PUT in others and some spell
casting.

NUMBER 2329
NAME Citidel, Tunnel
MONSTER_GROUP 20
INDOOR_FLOOR
DARKNESS
*DESCRIPTION_START
A pool of rancid  water has formed where condensing moisture collects as
it ran off the walls. The red stones of the citidal are particularly slick
here. A black fungus covers some of the stones.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT E 2328
EXIT W 2330
ITEM 0 324
EXTEND 0 of rancid water
PUT 0 198 ADJ1=255 VAL2=100 VAL3=226
ITEM 1 327 ADJ1=25

Conditional statements
----------------------

There are a number of control commands available within the scripting
languae, which will be discussed later in this section. Most of these
controls are best used within conditional statements. The script language
offers a variety of IF type expressions for allowing you to program what
happens when people do certain things or certain conditions are met.

As a matter of being orderly it is usual for conditional statements to be
placed at the end of the item or room block, after you have placed all of
the basic definitions.

Basic outline of a conditional statement

IF[arguments]
.
.    [control commands or additional conditions]
.
ENDIF

The following is a list of the available conditional statements.
IFITEM
IFTOUCH
IFVERB
IFVERB2
IFPREVERB
IFPREVERB2
IFVAR
IFNOITEM
IFFULLDESC
IFENTRY
IFSEEK
IFSAY

Variables and Arithmetic

Variables may be defined to keep track of numeric values. To define a
variable, simply place VARIABLE <varaible name> on a line by itself
anywhere in your script.

You can perform arithmetic functions on your variables or base conditional
statements upon them. All of them assume the format       [arithmetic
function] [destination variable name] source variable or value]. The
available arithmetic funstions are:

ADD   | Addition
DIV   | Division
EQUAL | Equal to
MOD   | Modulus division
MUL   | Multiplication
SUB   | Subtraction

Example:

VARIABLE TESTVAR
VARIABLE VAR2
EQUAL TESTVAR 3
EQUAL VAR2 7
ADD VAR2 3
MUL TESTVAR VAR2

The above would define two variables, "Testvar and Var2." Testvare is set
equal to 3 and Var2 equal to 7. The number 3 is then added to Var2 making
it 10. Testvar is then multiplied by Var2.

Internal Variables
------------------

A number of internal variables are already predefined to mean special
things. You may perform arithmetic on them, use as an argument in a
conditional statement, etc.

AGE        | Age                  LEV      | Level
AGI        | Agility              QUI      | Quickness
ALIGN      | Alignment            PER      | Perception
CON        | Constitution         RAC      | Race
EMP        | Empathy              STR      | Strength
FLAG1      |                      TIM      | Time of day
FLAG2      |                      WEA      | Weather
FLAG3      |                      WEI      | Weight
FLAG4      |                      WIL      | Willpower
GEN        | Gender               ORG      | Orginization
HEI        | Height
DAY        | Equals 1 if day, 0 if night
DATE       | Day of month
MONTH      | Month (1-13, 13=feast days)
YEAR       | Current Year
OBJWEIGHT  | Weight of current item
ITEMADJ1   | Adjective 1 of current item
ITEMADJ2   | Adjective 2 of current item
ITEMADJ3   | Adjective 3 of current item
SLEEPING   | Equals 1 if character is sleeping, o otherwise
MOVEABLE   | Equals 1 if the character is able to move, 0 otherwise
POSITION   | 0 = STANDING, 1 = SITTING, 2 = LAYING, 3 = KNEELING, 4 = FLYING
TEMP       | temperature in farenheit
MISTFORM   | Equals 1 if the character is in mistform
WOLFFORM   | Equals 1 if the character is in wolfform
SLIMEFORM  | Equals 1 if the character is in slimeform
OUTDOOR    | Equals 1 if the character is outside
WILDERNESS | Equals one if the player is outside and not in a
room               | that is not movement_astral
ASTRAL     | Equals 1 if the player is in a room that is
either                  | ASTRAL or MOVEMENT_ASTRAL
TERRAIN    | INDOOR_FLOOR=1
           | INDOOR_GROUND=2
           | FOREST=3
           | MOUNTAIN=4
           | PLAIN=5
           | SWAMP=6
           | OUTDOOR_OTHER=7
           | OUTDOOR_FLOOR=8
           | WASTE=9
           | JUNGLE=10
           | CAVE=11
           | ASTRAL=12
           | AERIAL=13
DUMMY1     |These are volatile, general use variables meant to be
DUMMY2     |used for temproray purposes so you don't need to keep
DUMMY3     |creating new ones for single-use along with script
DUMMY4     |commands like  DAMAGE.
DUMMY5     |
ITEMVAL1   |You may manipulate the VAL fields of an item directly as
ITEMVAL2   |normal internal valuables.
ITEMVAL3   |
ITEMVAL4   |
ITEMVAL5   |
ARCHNUM    |This is equal to the item archetype number of the
           |currently active item or -1 if there is no active item.
PLAYERNUM  |Equals -1 if there is no player active, or any other
           |number denoting the currently active player for the
           |script. This should be used with cevents that might
           |need a player active to perform a certain operation.

The variable RAC is to be used with these values.

1: Human                          5: Murg
2: Aelfen                         6: Drakin
3: Highlander                     7: Mechanoid
4: Wolfling                       8: Ephemeral
                                  9: Vampire

The variable WEA is to be used with these values.

0: Sunny                          4: Moderate rain
1: Partially cloudy               5: Heavy rain
2: Overcast                       6: Thunderstorm
3: Light rain                     7: Gale
                                  8: Hurricane
The following are examples of several kind of conditional statements.
Example of IFVERB

INUMBER 1622
NAME 166
WEIGHT 5
VOLUME 5
SUBSTANCE HARDMETAL
BOW_WEAPON
IFVERB CONCENTRATE -1
ECHO ALL The rifle comes to life and shoots a stream of bubbles all over.
ENDIF

Example of a cevent and IFSEEK:

CEVENT 17 30 312
   IFSEEK 110
      IFITEM -1 WIELDED
         RANDOM MUMBOJUM 1 5 0
         IFVAR MUMBOJUM = 1
            ECHO ALL The soulsword exudes a bone chilling aura.
         ENDIF
         IFVAR MUMBOJUM = 2
            ECHO ALL The soulsword flashes with black flames.
         ENDIF
        IFVAR MUMBOJUM = 3
            ECHO ALL The soulsword blasts your mind with thoughts of battle.
        ENDIF
        IFVAR MUMBOJUM = 4
            ECHO ALL The soulsword quivers with excitement at the thought of a battle.
        ENDIF
        IFVAR MUMBOJUM = 5
            ECHO ALL The soulsword groans with a need to taste blood.
        ENDIF
      ENDIF
   ENDIF

Example of multiple if statements in an item.

INUMBER 1617
NAME 32
WEIGHT 4
VOLUME 4
BOW_WEAPON
PARAMETER1 15
PARAMETER2 0
WORN_DON
SUBSTANCE INDESTRUCTABLE
VARIABLE SHOOTER
IFSEEK 180
IFVERB CONCENTRATE -1
IFVAR ITEMVAL5 ! TIM
ADD SHOOTER 1
IFVAR SHOOTER < 20
ECHO PLAYER May your aim be true.
SPELL 512 30
ECHO Player Let your enemies not harm you.
SPELL 133 50
ENDIF
IFVAR SHOOTER > 20
EQUAL ITEMVAL5 TIM
ENDIF
ENDIF
ENDIF
IFVERB LISTEN -1
ECHO PLAYER For you and only for you I shall reveal the full extent of my
ECHO PLAYER powers. If you have need of protection and steady hands you
have
ECHO player only to concentrate on me. Should you need your health restored
ECHO player polish me to a high luster. If you are bleeding and in need of
ECHO PLAYER staunching the flow of blood then sling me onto your back. If
you
ECHO PLAYER ever need light to see by gain my attention by tapping me.
ENDIF
IFVERB WEAR -1
ECHO PLAYER You sling the bow over your shoulder.
SPELL 342 50
ENDIF
IFPREVERB GIVE -1
ECHO PLAYER I am for you and no other. I shall be touched by no other hand.
ECHO OTHERS %n gets a glazed look for a moment and then nods his head
absently.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB DROP -1
ECHO PLAYER I shall not leave your hand we are as one now.
ECHO OTHERS %n looks like he is about to set the bow down and then changes
his mind.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB PUT -1
ECHO PLAYER No, I will not be seperated from you.
ECHO OTHERS %n grasps the bow tightly.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFITEM -1 WIELDED
IFVERB LOAD -1
ECHO ALL As the bow is loaded the arrow shimmers magically.
ENDIF
IFVERB RUB -1
ECHO PLAYER As you polish the bow lovingly, it glows a soft blue and
speaks to you:
ECHO PLAYER Let my power heal thy wounds.
ECHO OTHERS %n polishes the bow to a high luster, a soft blue glow
surrounds him.
EQUAL ROUNDTIME 20
SPELL 318
ENDIF
IFVERB TAP -1
ECHO OTHERS The bow flares with a brilliant blue light that coalesces into
a floating orb.
SPELL 113 50
ENDIF
ENDIF
ENDIF

Example of multiple if statements in a room.

NUMBER 3524
NAME Deep forest, grove
*DESCRIPTION_START
As you enter the grove the first thing you notice is the wildly dancing
balls
of light that surround the strange shadowy being that stands before you.
The
grove, itself, fills you with a sense of peace and well being that you
haven't
felt since you entered the heart of the forest.
*DESCRIPTION_END
FOREST
DAY_LIGHT
IFPREVERB CAST -1
ECHO PLAYER For some reason you can't bring yourself to break the harmony
ofthis place.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB ADVANCE -1
ECHO PLAYER You don't want to disturb this peacefull place with such
hostile action.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB HEAT -1
ECHO PLAYER You can't seem to focus properly.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
IFPREVERB FREEZE -1
ECHO PLAYER You can't seem to focus properly.
CLEARVERB
ENDIF
VARIABLE GENME
IFENTRY
IFVAR GENME < 1
ADD GENME 2
ECHO ALL You see the shadowy figure of the PathMaster before you.
GENMON 282
ENDIF
ENDIF
IFSAY SAMARDAZ_WERESLAYER?
ECHO ALL The PathMaster says, "Yes, I know of him. His body no longer
rests in the grove."
ENDIF
IFSAY WHERE_IS_HE?
ECHO ALL The PathMaster says, "His body now rests in the room with no
enterance and only one exit. I can open the way for you."
ENDIF
IFSAY WAY?
ECHO ALL The PathMaster says, "Very well, but know, the path is not
without its own risks."
ECHO ALL The PathMaster then waves his arms in a wide arching motion and
before you a shimmering arch appears.
NEWITEM 0 60 ADJ1=287 VAL2=3525
ENDIF

Monster Scripting
-----------------

Monster Adjectives:

Adjectives for monsters are difined similar to, but not the same as they
are for items. Everyone must be assigned numbers for monster adjectives.
To define a monster adjective you use MADJDEF # <adjective>.

Example:
MADJDEF 10 giant

To initiate a monster block you state MNUMBER #. Once again you must be
assigned Monster numbers.

NAME <name text>
Defines the name for the monster. Do not use a capital letter to start the
monsters name unless you are making it a UNIQUE monster.

ADJECTIVE #
Defines the adjective for the monster. Do not use Adjectives with Unique
monsters. This number is defined by the MADJ(monster adjectives).

HUMAN
This is a macro that defines the creatures body parts as humanoid.

AVINE
Defines the creatures body parts as birdlike.

ANIMAL
Defines a creatures body parts as a quadripedal animal.

PART #
This can be used in conjunction with or alone to define body parts on
creatures. The available body parts are as follows:

0 = head
1 = body
2 = back
3 = second head
4 = thorax
5 = right arm
6 = left arm
7 = right leg
8 = left leg
9 = right hind leg
10 = left hind leg
11 = right foreleg
12 = left foreleg
13 = right hand
14 = left hand
15 = right wing
16 = left wing
17 = tail
18 = right paw
19 = left paw


Body #
Defines the number of body points that are factored into the exp value of
the monster.

EXTRABODY
Defines an added amount of body point between 50-100% of the actual number
that is NOT factored into the exp value of the monster.

ATTACK1 #
Defines the monsters attack modifier of the creatures primary attack.

ATTACK2 #
Defines the attack modifier of the creatures secondary attack. This is not
used at the moment.

Defense #
Defines the monsters defend modifier.

STRATEGY #
This defines how the monster reacts in combat and overall behavior. The
following strategies are available.

1-100 Non-hostile, flee when attacked. (note: if 1-25, the creature will
also cry for help and alert legal authorities)

101-200 Non-hostile, defend themselves when attacked. 101-125 will cry for
help and alert legal authorities.

201-300 Animals that always flee even if not attacked but defend
themselves if attacked.

301-400 Hostile, flee when wounded. (group A)

401-500 Hostile, flee when wounded. (group B)

501-600 Hostile, fight to the death. (group A)

601-700 Hostile, fight to the death. (group B)

There is no destinction between group A and B at this time. The intention
of the difference in the future will be that Group A and group B will be
mutually hostile.

TREASURE #
Defines the treasure level for the creature. If this is zero, the creature
has no treasure.

Immunity (immunity #) (immunity level)
This defines a monster has having immunity to certain forms of attack. Or
in some cases extra susceptability to certain forms of attack. Immunity
level defines how susceptable or immune it is to that form of attack in
half-units. 2 is the default setting which means the creature is affected
2/2 (in full). 1 would be half damage. 3 would be 1 and 1/2 damage and 4
would be double damage. All immunities, unless noted otherwise, are set to
the default 2 except for #8 which is set to 0.


The available immunities are:

0 - Ensnaring attacks, particularly large or supernatural creatures would
ignore this form of attack.

1 - Crushing weapons.

2 - Edged weapons.

3 - Heat attacks.

4 - Electrical attacks.

5 - Cold attacks.

6 - Nervous system attacks. Creature would be immune to spells like charm,
sleep, psionic blast, etc. due to the lack of a normal nervous system.

7 - Life affecting. creatures would be immune to body destruction, poison,
disease and body restoration due to a lack of an active "life force" or
are to unlike normal life.

8 - Undead affecting. This is the only immunity that is default to 0 and
it must be set to a special value. When set to 3 it defines a creature as
a lesser undead, and includes creatures up to and including a lesser
wight. Setting it to 2 defines it as a greater undead such as a mummy,
lesser vampire, etc. Setting it to 1 should be reserved for extremely
powerful undead such as a lich, a greater vampire, etc.

9 - Susceptability to death criticals. If set to 0 the creature would not
receive a fancy death critical. This should be given to any creature that
lacks a normal humanoid or animal physiology.


RACE #
Defines the creatures racial group. At the moment this is only used in
conjunction with certain VALue settings on weapons for weapons of slaying.
The available races are as follows:

21 - extraplanar, creatures that come from other planes.

22 - Undead

23 - Arachnid

24 - Kvantar

25 - Troll

26 - Lycanthrope

27 - Giant

28 - Constructs (either magical or technological)

29 - Goblin

30 - Ogre

31 - Dragon
If you have a creature that you feel needs a new race identifier created
for it , please let Jon or Angela know.


WEAPON (weapon#) (adjective#) (weighted probability)
This defines the type of weapon the creature uses. Weapon# is the
archetype # for the weapon. Adjective defines a standard adjective for the
weapon and the weighted probability is the percent out of 100 that the
creature attacks with this weapon.

WEAPONPLUS #
Defines the creatures weapon as magical with # being the bonus of the
weapon. For obvious reasons you want to be carefull not to set this value
to high.


ARMOR #
Defines the percentage value of damage reduction that the monster receives.

MAGICWEAPON (1, 2 or 3)
If this is defined, then a magic weapon is needed to damage the creature.
If MAGICWEAPON 1, then any magic weapon will do. 2 requires a bonus of at
least +10. 3 requires a bonus of at least +21.

SKINADJ <#>
Defines the standard adjective number to attach to any items skinned from
a creature.

SKINITEM <item#> <probability> <coppervalue> <magic>
Item# defines the archetype number of a certain skin that is available on
a givenr monster. The "probability" is another weighted probability
similar to that used for distibuting weapon selection. "Coppervalue is the
items average value in copper. "Magic is a number thatwhich specifies the
magic content of the item. If 0 which most skins should be, the item is
non-magical. Otherwise it is a spell component.
Some item archetypes you may use for creature skins are:
504 = beard
505 = claw
506 = scalp
507 = scale
508 = ear
509 = pelt
510 = tooth
512 = dust
513 = talon
514 = hide
515 = hair
516 = beak
517 = feathers
518 = paw
519 = horn
520 = eye
521 = tongue
522 = tail
523 = skin
524 = tusk
525 = finger
526 = toe
527 = leg
528 = fangs


Discorporate
This indicates that if the monster is killed it will not leave a corpse
behind.

ETERNAL
This indicates that the creature will not be unloaded by the system until
it is killed.

GENDER <0, 1 or 2>
The default is 2. 0=Male, 1=Female

STEALABLE
This indicates the monster may be stolen from.

POISON <% chance> <x>
If defined, this provides a percent chance that a level x poison is
delivered to the victim upon being struck.

DISEASE <% chance> <x>
This is basically the same as POISON.

FATIGUE <%chance> <x>
This is the equivalent of a life draining attack.

RESIST <x>
This defines the creatures magic resistance.

SPEED <x>
The default setting is 3. It defines how fast the creature attacks and
moves. 1 is fastest and 4 or more is for extremely slow creatures.

*DESCRIPTION_START
Blah blah blah
*DESCRIPTION_END
Standard description field just like it is used for rooms.


HIDESKILL <X>
This defines a percentage chance that the creature will be able to hide.
it is also used to define the creatures skill at backstab. X is the base
chance. Warning: do not define X above 100.

GUARD <X>
defines what creature this monster will guard where X is the monster
number that is to be guarded.

UNIQUE
Indicates that this creature is unique and has a personal rather than
general name. Use this definition BEFORE defining the creatures name.

SPELLCASTING CREATURES
----------------------

MANA <X>
Defines the number of mana points a monster has.

SPELLUSE <% chance>
Defines the chance of the monster using its spells as opposed to its
weapon or special attack.

SPELLSKILL <X>
Defines the base spellcraft skill the creature has.

CASTLEVEL <x>
Defines the duration of a creatures spell.

NONDISRUPTABLE
This indicates that the creature's spell will not be disrupted by an
attack.

SILENCEIGNORE
This indicates that the Silence spell will not affect the creature's
ability to cast a spell.

SPELL <Spell#>
Grants the creature the given spell. NOTE: Not all spells will work but
almost all offensive and defensive spells will work.

DEFINING SPECIAL ATTACKS
------------------------

Besides giving a creature spells to cast, you may give it a "special
attack form" which is an attack that always works.

SPECUSE <%chance>
Defines the percent chance that the creature will choose to use its
special attack in preference to other attacks.

SPECUSES <x>
Limits the creatures ability to use its special attack to x times.

SPECBASE <x>
Sets the <minimum> damage that this attack will do.

SPECDMG <x>
Sets the additional <random> damage range that this attack will do.

SPECDMGTYPE <Heat, cold, slash, electric>
Sets the damage type for special attack forms.

TEXX <special attack text output..>
This text assumes the following format. "%s blah blah blah %s." You must
have the two %s strings in there. They have nothing to do with the echo
command uses. They are replaced with the attacking creatures name and the
victim creatures name respectively. do not include quotes in your
definition.
Example:
TEXX %s breathes a gout of flame at %s!

REDEFINING the default text fields for a monster
------------------------------------------------

The text fields may be redefined by using the TEX? commands.
Example:
TEXH A thief fails to sink into the shadows.

Redefines the text for a certain creature that is shown when that creature
fails its % chance to hide. The available redefinitions are as follows.

TEXB   Text displayed when the creature is leading a group and its group arrives.
TEXC   Text displayed when the creature is leading a group and its group leaves the room.
TEXV   Text output when a creature prepares a spell when it is invisible.
TEXH   When the creature fails to hide.
TEXX   When the creature uses its special attack.
TEXE   Creature enters a room.
TEXI   When an attack is made with a weapon that is not enchanted powerfully enough to affect the
	   monster.
TEXQ   When  the creature fails its spellcraft check.
TEXZ   A text field output once and a while when the monster is in the room with a dead person.
	   Somewhere in this string must be a %s(has nothing to do with the ECHO usage %s) which
	   indicates that the name of the creature who is to be the target of the monster's mockery
	   should be replaced there.
TEX1  \
TEX2   \ These define some text which can be output once and a while
TEX3   / selected randomly. They provide you with the ability to
TEX4  /  animate your creatures.

TEXD   Text output when the creature is killed.
TEXF   Output when the creature flees. Don't add extra spaces or punctuation on the end of
	   this line, since the game needs to append the direction of movement. For example:
TEXF A goblin scrambles Might generate "A goblin scrambles north."
TEXM   Output when the creature moves. Like TEXF, don't add extra spaces or punctuations on the end.
TEXG   Output when the creature is generated in the room.
TEXS   Output when the creature prepares a spell.
TEXL   Output when the creature gestures (casts its spell).
TEXA   When the creature advances. Similar to TEXF and TEXM don't add extra spaces or punctuations.
TEXR   When the creature retreats.

New stuff: v2.40
----------------

New commands
------------

@lwho:  Shows a list of all players, with their room #, status
prompt and name of the room they are in.

@qstat <player #>:  Show a "quick" version of the players stats.

@num <Full player name>:  Returns the player # of the player name
requested.

@register <player #>:  Registers a player for paramutual betting.  A
player is removed from the betting roster automatically by exiting
the room.  The odds for each player are relative to the amount bet
on each player.   Payoff is divided to winning betters relative to
the amount they bet, taken from 95% of the total bets placed (5% is
skimmed off the top).

BET <player name>:  Allows a player to place a bet on anyone registered
for paramutual betting.

ODDS:  Shows the odds for anyone registered for paramutual betting.


New scripting commands
----------------------

Item definitions
----------------

TECH
Defines an item as a "tech" treasure item.

PORTAL_UP
Same as PORTAL, except phrases the output as the person/group going up
something.

PORTAL_DOWN
Same as PORTAL, except phrases the output as the person/group going down
something.

PORTAL_OVER
Same as PORTAL, except phrases the output as the person/group going over
something.


Room definitions
----------------

DEEPCAVE
Defines a room as a cave so far under the ground that conjuration and
teleportation spells will not function.

ARENA
Defines a room as being a non-lethal arena area.  In this type of
room, anyone who would normally die instead collapses and is
carried to the room defined by DROPLOC.

BUY_TECH
Defines a room as having a merchant who will purchase TECH items.

ECHOCHAN <x>
If set to a non-zero number, ECHOCHAN causes all text output to the
room to be echoed to all rooms that are in the channel indicated
(as defined by the CHANNEL definition).


New monster definitions
-----------------------

WEAPONPLUS <x>
Applies a magic bonus of X to any weapon that monster wields.  Be
careful giving this bonus to an item that could be picked up by the
player after the monster is dead, because it would be an easy way for
them to get a magical weapon.


New general scripting
---------------------

SHOWROOM <x>
Echos the room description of room x to the current player as if
they had typed "look" in that room.


New monster scripting
---------------------

ZAPMON:  Deletes the monster from the room as well as anything it was
         carrying.

DEAD:  A variable: equals one if the monster is dead, zero otherwise.


New variables
-------------

ROUNDTIME
The current player's round time, in seconds.  This variable may only
be set, not examined.

ARENADEATH
Equals one if the current player's death was trapped by an ARENA type
room.


Legends version 5.12
====================

New command:   @echoplr <num> <text.....>
 Sends a message to the player specified by <num>.  Works the same as
 @whisper, except there is no preceding message telling the player what
 GM the message was generated for;  thus, you can use it for special
 effects directed at one player in particular.

Modified command:  @qstat <num>
 The "quick stat" command now shows the player's NovaLink user-id.

New scripting capabilities
==========================

1. Ability to seperate game areas into distinct geographic/economic regions

REGIONDEF <x> <other data...>

Defines a "region" number "x" (which may be 0-250).  A region is a set
of rooms that share a number of configurable parameters.  The available
settings are as follows:

  REGIONDEF x WEATHER

  Specifies that weather will occur in this region.

  REGIONDEF x EXTRAPLANAR

  Specifies that your region is extraplanar.  This has a number of
  effects, but the most important is that characters travelling here
  are limited in skill use as per the Legends version notes regarding
  the transcendence skill.

  REGIONDEF x SEASONS

  Specifies that your region has seasons or not.  You still need to
  specify the base temperature for the different parts of the year as shown
  below.

  REGIONDEF x TIME

  Specifies whether your region experiences the passage of time observable
  through the movement of the sun.

  REGIONDEF x WINTERTEMP <base temp>
  REGIONDEF x SUMMERTEMP <base temp>
  REGIONDEF x SPRINGTEMP <base temp>
  REGIONDEF x AUTUMNTEMP <base temp>

  Defines the base temepature in farenheit for a given region.  This
  base temperature is used to determine a region's environmental
  temperature on a daily basis.  The formula used for the actual
  temperature is:

         actual_temp = base_temp + rnd(15) + rnd(15);

  So if you put "20" for the base temperature, the possible range of
  actual temperatures for your region would be 22-50, with the most
  likely average temperature being around 36.

  REGIONDEF x PRECIPITATION <precipitation level>

  Precipitation level is simply a relative scale measuring how much
  rain/snow will fall in a given region.  A precipitation level of 0
  would be "normal" (equal to the precipitation level used in the game
  so far).  The closer to 10 you get, the less likely it is to create
  precipitation at any time and the more likely it is for existing
  precipitation to cease.  If you specify a negative number, it will be
  increasingly likely to have precipitation at any time.  If you specify
  a precipitation of 10, it would probably never rain.

  REGIONDEF x TREASURE <percent of local currency>

  This is only valid in regions 0-10.  When this is specified, it allows
  you to state what percent of "local currency" (as defined with a
  MONDEYDEF with the same money definition number as the region number)
  appears in the pockets of monsters genned in the region.  Just state
  "100" to have a 100% chance if you want to have local currency only.
  Non-local currency is simply the common gold, silver and copper piece.

  REGIONDEF x DEPART <room>

  Specifies the room number a player will be moved to if they use the
  DEPART command while dead.  If room == 0, then it is impossible for
  them to depart in the specified region.

  REGIONDEF x TELEPORT ALLOWED    or...
  REGIONDEF x TELEPORT DISABLED

  Specifies whether you region permits teleportation -within- your
  region or not.  Teleportation is never permitted between regions.

  REGIONDEF x SUMMONING ALLOWED  or...
  REGIONDEF x SUMMONING DISBABLED

  Specified whether you want to allow summoning spells to function
  within your region.

  REGIONDEF x WELLOFLIFE ALLOWED   or...
  REGIONDEF x WELLOFLIFE REVERSED  or...
  REGIONDEF x WELLOFLIFE DISABLED

  Specified whether the Well of Life spell works or not, or if you'd
  like its effect reversed (so that it functions as Raise Undead).

  REGIONDEF x FIRE <percent effectiveness>

  Specifies the percent effectiveness of fire-base spells and other
  effects in region x.  For example, a "REGIONDEF 15 FIRE 50" would
  make it so that fire spells would do only half damage in region 15.

  REGIONDEF x COLD <percent effectiveness>

  Specifies the percent effectiveness of cold-base spells and other
  effects in region x.

  REGIONDEF x ELECTRIC <percent effectiveness>

  Specifies the percent effectiveness of electrical and energy spells
  and other effects in region x.

  REGIONDEF x ENCHANTMOD <penalty>

  Specifies the penalty to apply against enchanted weapons in region x.
  It will never penalize an enchanted weapon to lower than a bonus of 0.
  For example, you could make it so that all weapons are dropped in
  bonus by 20 to a minimum of 0 in region 15 by doing
  "REGIONDEF 15 ENCHANTMOD 20".  Then, +20 weapons would become +0,
  +15 would become +0, +25 would become +5, etc.


REGION <x>

When inserted in a room definition block, this defines the region of
the world that the room belongs to.  If not specified, the default is 0.
Defining a region has the following effects:


  - Temperature, weather, passage of time, spells, etc. are modified
      as per the REGIONDEF for the region.
  - Characters cannot teleport or scry characters in another region.
  - Regions numbered between 0-9 are a special type;  a room in a
    region between 0 and 9 use a money type the same as their region
    number.  For example, if you've got a room in region 5, and you have
    a shop there, they will use money type 5 (see below).

    * * * YOU MUST HAVE A REGION NUMBER ASSIGNED TO YOU * * *


2. Ability to define new units of currency for new regions


MONEYDEF <x> <name> <exchange rate> <item#>

  Defines a type of money.  "X" is a number from 1 to 9.  This number
  is equivalent to a type of money native to a given region number 1-9
  (as above).  "Name" is the singular name of the currency.  "Exchange
  rate" is a number from 1 to 100, specifying the number of units of
  this new type of currency that are roughly equivalent to one gold
  piece (of base currency).  The "exchange rate" is used in only two
  places at this time:  the cost of getting healed by a physician, and
  the amount of treasure in this currency unit generated by a monster
  that carries this type of currency relative to standard (base)
  coin types.  The "item#" field specifies the actual item archetype
  to use when creating this type of money in tangible form.

  Here is an example of a new money type now in use:

  MONEYDEF 2 kragenmark 12 1869

  (This defines a unit of currency called the kragenmark, used in
   region #2, of which 12 equals one gold piece;  item number 1869
   is the "physical" item archetype to be used when creating this
   type of money in tangible form)

    * * * DON'T DEFINE A MONEY TYPE WITHOUT AN ASSIGNMENT * * *

  After you create a unit of currency, you still need to make a new
  item archetype and noun for the currency if you want people to be
  able to get it from treasure, pick it up, drop it, etc.  Just create
  a "MONEY" type item.  The PARAMETER2 field specifies the unit of
  currency the item is for.  Example:

  NOUNDEF 1543 kragenmark
  ;
  INUMBER 1869
  NAME 1543
  MONEY
  WEIGHT 1
  VOLUME 1
  PARAMETER2 2
  ARTICLE SOME

3. New room modifiers

HEALER

  Defines a room as a place a character can get healed by a physician
  by sitting down.  There should only be one of these per region
  number 0-9, or else it won't know what money to use.  The only
  region you can go into 'debt' in with the healers is region 0.

BANK

  Defines a room as a place a character can perform banking.  There
  should only be one bank per region number 0-9, or else it will mix
  their money up between banks.  Each bank is limited to one type of
  currency only.  Characters may have a bank account for each currency
  type, but they can only have a safety deposit box at one bank at
  a time (due to system limitations).

4. New variables

SUBMITTING              Equals 1 if the character is submitting
DEPARTROOM              Equals the last room the character departed
                        from, or 0 if they have not departed recently.
REGION                  Equals the number of the region the character
                        is presently standing in.

Legends version 5.30
====================

New definitions:

REGIONDEF x MINE_ADJ adj#   Places the adjective specified into the first
                            adjective field of any material mined in
                            region x.

MINE_ELEMENT [adj] [val3]   If a weaponsmith forges a weapon created
                            from a material containing adjective
                            number 'adj' in its first adjective slot,
                            then it will set the 'val3' field on the
                            finished weapon as specified.  The val5
                            field is set to a value relative to the
                            smith's skill.  The effect is to make it
                            so materials mined from a certain region
                            can be made into weapons with elemental
                            criticals.

OUTOFBODY                   A room type modifier;  with this one,
                            the player has no apparent skills,
                            spells, psionic disciplines or inventory.

New script commands:

IFIN [item tag #] [var]  This if statement is true if the item archetype
             specified by 'var' is located inside the item specified
             by the item tag number.  If it is found, the "current
             item" is set to the first such item located.

IFCARRY [var]  This if statement is true if the item archetype specified
             by 'var' is located in the current player's inventory.
             If it is found, the "current item" is set to the first
             such item located.

RECALC       This causes the player's offensive and defensive
             statistics to be recalculated based on their
             current environment.  This is mainly important
             for making sure peoples OM/DM are correct after
             passing through planar portals.

New variables:

SPELLNUM     The number of the spell the player is currently
             preparing.  This can be set to 0 to simulate 'releasing'
             the spell (or you could set it to another spell for
             a real surprise).  Could be used in scripts with an
             IFPREVERB CAST to see if the character is using a
             particular spell...

WIELDED      Equals the item archetype number of whatever the
             person is wielding in their 'primary' hand, or zero
             if they are not wielding anything.

DISGUISED    Equals one if the player is disguised in any way
             (with disguise skill or invisible).

WEALTH1      The amount of wealth they have of a particular type.
WEALTH2
WEALTH3
WEALTH4
WEALTH5
WEALTH6
WEALTH7
WEALTH8
WEALTH9

Legends version 4.80 features some things including the major
psionics update.  Please see the version notes on the LEGENDS
page for more info.

I've added an @psi command for granting/revoking psionic disciplines.
It works similarly to @grantspell.

The following are the new psionic script commands for monsters:

PSIRESIST <x>
Defines the creature's psionic resistance.  If you don't specify
any, it will default to the same as its normal magic resistance.

PSI <x>
The number of psi points the creature has.

DISCIPLINE <x>
Gives the creature the psionic discipline # you specify.

PSIUSE <x>
Specifies a percentage (1-100) of the time that this creature will
opt to use psionics in preferences to other attack modes.

PSISKILL <x>
The total chance that the psionic creature has when invoking a
psionic power.  Powerful psionic creatures should have well over
a 100 so as to defeat a player's natural resistance to psionics.

PSILEVEL <x>
The creature's effective skill level in the Mind over Matter skill.
This is used for determining the effectiveness of Cryokinetics,
Pyrokinetics, Electrify and Kinetic Thrust.

How to design a good psionic creature:

Psionic creatures should always have at least one psionic attack
discipline for overcoming a psionicist's defense modes;  it should
also have a defense mode of its own.  Then just give it whatever
you think it should have.  It will probably take some testing to
find out what monsters can use well.  I've tried to build in
some intelligence for monsters so that they'll make wise selections
from the disciplines you give them based on their situation.

One difference with psionic creatures v. magic creatures:  if you
give them a defense discipline (be it a mental defense or the
physical defenses), they get genned with those disciplines already
active.  Make sure you give psionic monsters enough psi to maintain
whatever they have.

Don't give monsters non-battle psionic disciplines (like levitation,
flight, strengthen steel, etc.).  Don't give them Domination either,
because they aren't smart enough to make use of it properly (at this
time anyway).


